Montana Mountain Bike Alliance shared Southwest Montana Mountain Bike Association's post.
March 19 at 4:59pm

This formal recognition has such positive significance. No bicyclist around deserves more accolades than Corey! Not enough good can be stated about Corey and his volunteer pursuits. This award is priceless.

Southwest Montana Mountain Bike Association
Nonprofit Organization
Southwest Montana Mountain Bike Association
March 19 at 7:44am

COMMUNITY BUILDER: Corey Biggers

In the past year SWMMBA occasionally introduces our members/followers to individuals that are doing great things for the region...al MTB community, we call these people COMMUNITY BUILDERS. Today we are introducing you to Corey Biggers.

Corey (with friends) has organized the clearing of the Lionhead/Henry's Mountains and the segments CDT that run from Yellowstone Park Boundary past the Centennial Mountains for more than a decade. Corey is so passionate about trail clearing and maintenance he has engineered custom aluminum saw scabbards for fat bikes, exclusively rides a Salsa Cycles fat bike, organizes monumental work parties and spends almost every summer weekend clearing trails. Many through CDT travelers have passed on a story or two of encountering a friendly crew of MTBers with chainsaws who have made that segment of their long journey all the more memorable and much more passable.

Two years ago Corey started a group with his father in-law Clark Kinney, The Backcountry Hikers, Bicyclists and Equestrians. The men were concerned that there was too much separation between trail user groups and that need to change they wanted to BUILD A COMMUNITY of diverse trail users.

With some of the larger trail clearing and maintenance projects Clark and Corey organize trail users with hoof, foot and tire to work together to accomplish far more together than they could sepperatly. Lionhead is the perfect illustration of this COMMUNITY BUILDING, Clark organizes equestrians to cary saws and other equipment to the shoulder of Targhee Peak from Mile Creek, MTBers then pick up the equipment and proceed to clear milage (in the 20 to 30 mile range) that would not be practical for the horses to travel in a day.

This collaborative leadership created by Corey, Clark, Debbie and Greg Beardslee's involvement with SWMMBA, Montana Mountain Bike Alliance, Backcountry Hikers, Bicyclists and Equestrians and Backcountry Horseman, Gallatin Chapter builds cooperation and enables big projects to happen. This year three big collaborative trail work projects are on the in the works : South Cottonwood (6/30), Lionhead (7/20-22) and First Yellow Mule(7/28) watch our page for details.

On March 17th, MTBers, Forest Service personal and equestrians came together (50 +/- participants) participate in a clinic taught by Jon Ensign to introduce horse trainers to the compassionate method of desensitizing their animals to MTBs and other novel modes of trail use they may encounter. The weekend was organized by Corey Biggers, Debbie Kinney-Moran and Clark Kinney. Cory is so passionate about this work he and the business he works with sponsored this event. Elite Kubota, LLC Rocky Mountain Truck Center

At the end of the clinic Jarrod Hanson from the Ashton, Island Park and Dubois district of the Caribou-Targhee National Forest presented Clark Kinney and Corey with a plaque acknowledging the districts gratitude for the 12 years of dedication to clearing trails*. Corey is so humble he is already claiming the plaque is dedicated to all of us who have followed him into the woods, hoisted a saw or picked up a shovel.

If you want to support endeavorers like our work with Corey, SWMMBA Copper City Trails, the Pump Track, etc. Please come out to our screening of Trails In Motion Film Festival MTB on March 21: https://www.facebook.com/events/1529064500534675/

Thank you Corey for all of your hard work and being one of the nicest people we know!

*As a side note we also want to point out that the trails Corey has been recognized for clearing are endangered for MTB access as they are in a RWA or on the CDT. Thank you if you wrote letter to the Custer-Gallatin National Forest regarding the management of RWA's.

March 5

5 Minute Drill!

Please insert your [NAME] (in two places) and Copy & Paste text below into Link attached link by midnight tonight!

SAMPLE COMMENT:

...

To: Custer-Gallatin National Forest
Re: CGNF Forest Plan Revision-Recommended Wilderness Areas
Date: March 5th, 2018

Dear Forest Plan Revision Team:

Thank you for the opportunity to review and comment on the Proposed Action. My name is [NAME] and I am an avid mountain biker who believes that our quiet, non-motorized, muscle-powered, trail-based recreation is appropriate into our wildest, most remote public lands.

In the face of increasing wildlife habitat concerns, recreational pressures and climate change, I believe that pro-active, science-based management of our public lands is preferred to the restrictive and bicycle banning Recommended Wilderness Areas. I believe that if land managers are given the discretion to make localized decisions, with the support of local stakeholders, they will be more responsive and accountable to our precious public lands.

I applaud the acknowledgement of the importance of continued bicycle access to the Continental Divide National Scenic Trail (CDNST) in Mile Creek, and support the Proposed Actions direction that keeps the Mile Creek section bicycle friendly but believe the Proposed Action does not go far enough to manage this wild area in a socially responsible manner. The Proposed Action would adjust the RWA boundary to the north edge of the CDNST and eliminate cycling in the remaining Lionhead RWA. For decades bicyclists have respectfully ridden, maintained and cherished the backcountry loop option using Sheep Creek (#218) and West Fork of Watkins Creek (#216) in addition to the Mile Creek CDNST.

I request that the CGNF Forest Planners create a Lionhead Backcountry Area for the entire Lionhead RWA similar to the innovative Proposed Action used for the Buffalo Horn Backcountry Area. This Backcountry Area designation would more accurately fit the present low-impact, quiet recreational use in the area, and will allow local land managers the responsive discretion to pro-actively manage ALL users in this landscape. A Lionhead Backcountry Area would allow continued bicycle use and avoids the blanket bicycle ban by the proposed RWA.

Thank you for your consideration,
[NAME]

January 27

Let's be involved. The Custer-Gallatin Forest Plan is being reviewed soon. Show up to these meetings and have a say in keeping trails open for mountain biking. As this video shows, there are plenty of folks who would like to close trails in a quest for wilderness over inclusive forms of quiet recreation, which pretty much means mountain biking. Let Southwest Montana Mountain Bicycle Association know which trails are important to you. Get involved in this growing club and learn about upcoming access issues and next year's projects. And as Montana Mountain Bike Alliance, when we learn of new specific issues of concern in addition to the Hyalite Porcupine Buffalo Horn Wilderness Study Area, we'll keep you updated.

Montana Mountain Bike Alliance added 4 new photos.
January 19

January 18, Missoula, Montana. Clearwater National Forest held an outreach meeting in Missoula to hear from concerned citizens about access and preservation of the Great Burn Recommended Wilderness. As many of you know, Region One of the Forest Service has an overly restrictive, and possibly illegal method of managing public access into Recommended Wilderness. This important meeting marked the first time the Clearwater National Forest actually took to heart the concerned citi...zens of Montana, who have a back door to this Idaho Forest. The Forest sent a top team of specialists to cover this meeting and they did a thorough job in capturing the public's temperature regarding the issues of land closures. The meeting was well attended by environmental professionals and volunteers who have worked hard for years to achieve a Great Burn Wilderness. The meeting was also attended by a large contingent of snowmobilers and a sizable group of mountain bike riders, all of whom spoke for fair access consideration. The Forest specialists not only recorded the concerns of all but also opened the door for a collaborative to form and begin to work towards a compromise. Missoula area mountain bikers are on task!
